'''James Stanley Lyons Mitchell''' (born 19 October 1946) is a former [[Irish people|Irish]] first-class [[cricket]]er.
Mitchell was born at [[Cullion]] in [[County Tyrone]] in October 1946, and was educated at [[Foyle College]] in [[Derry]].<ref name="CE">{{cite web|url=https://www.cricketeurope.com/IRELAND/PLAYERS/526/index.shtml |title=Player profile: John Stanley Lyons Mitchell |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref> He first played club cricket for [[Donemana Cricket Club|Donemana]], before moving to [[Belfast]] to study at [[Queen's University Belfast|Queen's University]], where he joined the [[Queen's University Cricket Club|university cricket club]].<ref name="CE"/> He later made his debut for [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] in a minor match against the [[Netherlands national cricket team|Netherlands]] at Amstelveen on Ireland's 1974 tour of the Netherlands.<ref name="CE"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/26/26842/Miscellaneous_Matches.html |title=Miscellaneous Matches played by Stanley Mitchell |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref> Later that saem year, he made a single appearance in [[first-class cricket]] for Ireland against [[Scotland cricket team|Scotland]] at [[Cambusdoon|Alloway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/26/26842/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Stanley Mitchell |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref> Playing as a [[Batting_order_(cricket)#Middle_order|middle order batsman]], Mitchell batted twice in the match. He was dismissed in Ireland's first-innings for 2 runs by [[Jack Clark (Scottish cricketer)|Jack Clark]], while in their second-innings he was dismissed by [[Frank Robertson (cricketer)|Frank Robertson]] for 27 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/34/34576.html |title=Scotland v Ireland, 1974 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref> He later moved to [[Dublin]], where he played club cricket for [[Phoenix Cricket Club|Phoenix]].<ref name="CE"/> Outside of cricket, Mitchell runs his own business called Dublin Grass Machinery.<ref name="CE"/> After retiring from playing, he became a national selector.<ref name="CE"/> In 2005 he served as president of the [[Cricket Ireland|Irish Cricket Union]], helping to organise the [[2005 ICC Trophy]], which Ireland hosted.<ref name="CE"/>
